Security hauled her out of the room, too, along with about a dozen other demonstrators, many of them members of Black Lives Matter.
As the LA County district attorney’s primary approaches, tensions have been mounting between her office and Black Lives Matter protesters.
It’s “the single most important DA race in the country,” says Patrisse Cullors, a co-founder of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Los Angeles voters elected Lacey as district attorney in 2012, just before the rise of the Black Lives Matter movement.
But it was not enough for some Black Lives Matter activists, who remembered the hundreds of other cases she dismissed.